Based on the code you provided, your application does not have any User Authentication logic (Sign In/Login). Therefore, Firestore blocks the connection because the default security rules usually require a user to be logged in.

To fix this error and allow your dashboard to work, you need to update your Firestore Security Rules in the Firebase Console to allow **public access** (Test Mode).

### **Steps to fix:**

1.  Go to the [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/).
2.  Select your project (**maniranjanpo**).
3.  In the left sidebar, click on **Build** -> **Firestore Database**.
4.  Click on the **Rules** tab at the top.
5.  Delete the existing code and paste the following rules:

```javascript
rules_version = '2';

service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    // Match any document in the database
    match /{document=**} {
      // Allow anyone to read or write (Create, Update, Delete)
      // CAUTION: This makes your database public.
      allow read, write: if true;
    }
  }
}
```

6.  Click **Publish**.

### **Why this is necessary:**
Your `App.tsx` initializes Firestore but never calls an authentication method (like `signInWithEmailAndPassword`). Without these rules, Firestore treats every request as "unauthorized" and blocks it. These new rules tell Firestore: "Allow any user who has my API key to read and modify the data."

